The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 More get hooked to phones

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Feb. 8: India has 9.29 crore telephone subscribers (both mobile and landline) with the teledensity nudging up to 8.59 per cent by the end of 2004.

 The teledensity was 7 per cent in March 2004. 

 During the April to December period, more than 164 lakh telephones have been added. In December alone, operators added more than 23 lakh new customers.

 Mobile phones accounted for more than 87 per cent of the phones added during the year. The number of mobile phones (including wireless in local loop-mobile) as on December 31, 2004 has been placed at over 4.8 crore.

 Private operators accounted for 77 per cent of the expansion during these nine months. The private sector has provided 4.26 crore phones till December. This is about 46 per cent of the total phones in the country.

 In rural areas, only Bharat Sanchar Nigam Ltd (BSNL) has provided direct exchange lines and village public telephones (VPTs). BSNL has provided 7.65 lakh village telephones during the nine-month period against 4.73 lakh additional telephones provided in rural areas during April-December 2003. 

 During December Bharat Sanchar Nigam has provided 3,138 VPTs.




